summary: One of Peter's worries is that those he loves will be taken away. I think after his parents leaving him, Uncle Ben dying, he has...
body:
One of Peter’s worries is that those he loves will be taken away. I think after his parents leaving him, Uncle Ben dying, he has some pretty strong abandonment issues and when he looses his girlfriends (or they leave him), it just adds to that sense of being left alone which manifests into him thinking there’s something wrong with him and that’s why people leave.

And then Deadpool shows up.

Deadpool who can’t die. Deadpool who comes back with a vengeance. Deadpool who likes staying with Peter and being with him.

Peter keeps waiting for Wade to leave so he distances himself, he keeps Wade at arms length because like so many people in his life, Wade will see something in him that everybody else has seen and he’ll leave Peter and Peter is just waiting for the day for it to happen.

But Wade doesn’t leave. He stays. And it terrifies Peter because what if he lets Wade get close and then the universe pulls the rug from under them?

So Peter keeps Wade at arms length, and uses humour as a way of protecting his heart, and enjoys whatever time he and Wade have together, holding it close to his heart because its only a matter of time before Wade leaves and Peter will be on his own again.

summary: Marvel Comics presenta el primer tráiler de Spider-Geddon
title: Marvel Comics presenta el primer tráiler de Spider-Geddon
body:
New Post has been published on http://arata.lat/marvel-comics-presenta-spider-geddon/

Marvel Comics presenta el primer tráiler de Spider-Geddon

La New York Comic Con, trajo muchas noticias nuevas y frescas para el mundo del noveno arte y sin duda el nuevo tráiler del evento que Marvel Comics presentó del vecino arácnido, será algo de lo que se hable con la próxima película Spider-verse.

El  evento comenzará el próximo miércoles 10 de octubre con el tomo 1 Spider-Geddon. En el tráiler, el guionista Christos Gage, el Editor Ejecutivo Nick Lowe y el Editor en Jefe C.B. Cebulski hablan sobre por qué Spider-Geddon es emocionante y diferente.

Además, nos recuerdan que veremos muchos personajes arácnidos y diferentes variaciones de Spidey, incluyendo al Spider-Man del juego de PlayStation 4.

blog.name: delayedcritique
blog.title: Delayed Critique
blog.description: Where you can find all of my reviews

title: VENOM REVIEW
body:
“The most entertaining bad Marvel movie”

BY COLLIN DE LADE

After a decade of advancements to the comic book genre, “Venom” reverts back to the subpar quality and misguided tone of the comic book movies of the early 2000’s. However, what completely saves the film is the excellent performance from Tom Hardy and the equally entertaining Venom character. Without Hardy and Venom working so well, “Venom” would have been a complete mess.

“Venom” is the latest Marvel property disconnected from the Marvel Cinematic Universe telling the origin story of Eddie Brock (Tom Hardy) and how he got connected with the dangerous symbiote, Venom. After losing his job and his girlfriend, Eddie is down on his luck trying to make ends meet. After a random encounter with Dr. Dora Skirth (Jenny Slate) where she hires Eddie to break into a top-secret lab, Venom aggressively connects with Eddie along with infecting his body and mind. Having to adapt to the symbiote bonded to him, Eddie is also on the run from the sinister Carlton Drake (Riz Almed) who’s trying to get back his experiment before his illegal secrets are revealed.

The two sole survivors of “Venom” abysmal script is Hardy and Venom. If any film showcases how much of a powerhouse Hardy is in Hollywood right now, it’s “Venom”. Any other actor would have crumbled with the poorly written, misguided script, but Hardy put everything he’s got to offer to carry the film out from the grave. Even in the most idiotic scenes, Hardy manages to make it work. Notice how the character Eddie Brock is not receiving praise, as the anti-hero, tough persona the character was advertised as is missing from the final product. The character acts closer to Doctor Steven Strange rather than Eddie Brock from the comics.

As for the titular character, Venom shares the same praises and complaints as Hardy; great performance with a goofy, misguided written tone. As someone who enjoyed “Spider-Man 3”, I finally understand why fans were angry at the portrayal of Venom. I was unaware that Venom is a separate character from Eddie Brock. Originally believing that Venom was an alternate identity to Brock like Spider-Man was to Peter Parker, I was pleasantly surprised to see in “Venom” that the symbiote was a fleshed out, entertaining character. Even though Venom never reaches a frightening level and plays more like a goofball, the character is pleasantly fun to watch.

Unfortunately, everything besides Hardy and Venom is a complete mess. From the forgettable female love interest from Michelle Williams to the purely evil Carlton Drake villain; the supporting cast is downright terrible. Williams’ character is the most generic, uninteresting lover interest to exist in any mediocre superhero movie. Besides one sole character trait with knowing Venom’s weakness, she is completely useless and demands to be written out of the film. As for the villain, Carlton is as bland and forgettable as you can get. Every moment Carlton is onscreen doesn’t work in the slightest. This villain received no love from the filmmakers who’s sole purpose is to be the forgettable first villain to lead into the more interesting sequel villain.

Two big criticisms “Venom” received before its release is the lack of a connection to Spider-Man and how the film was toned down from an R-rating. As obvious and necessary as it would be to have a Spider-Man backstory for Venom, the alternate origin story for Venom is passable. I am curious why Sony, who still owns a portion of the rights to Spider-Man, didn’t tie the character into their new franchise, but it’s a moot point now. As for the tone down rating, “Venom” really would have benefited from being a film for 17 years old and up. Especially knowing there are 40 minutes cut out of the final film, this final product in theaters doesn’t feel like the desired cut.

“Venom” is a pure example of a terrible film saved by a few great aspects. Hardy and Venom are the only redeeming aspects of the film. Without these two good aspects, this movie would be unwatchable; luckily, its the two main stars of the film. With days between seeing the film and writing this review, it has been difficult whether to declare people to see the film or not. As much as there are some very embarrassing moments, Hardy and Venom really do redeem the terrible parts. Predicting that an extended cut is coming in the near future, I would wait to see “Venom” until it’s available to rent. Maybe people will downright hate it and find the chemistry between Brock and Venom completely idiotic, which is completely understandable. If you’re willing to take a risk in seeing what side you land on, check out “Venom” at your most convenience. 

6/10

“The most entertaining bad Marvel movie”

BY COLLIN DE LADE

After a decade of advancements to the comic book genre, “Venom” reverts back to the subpar quality and misguided tone of the comic book movies of the early 2000’s. However, what completely saves the film is the excellent performance from Tom Hardy and the equally entertaining Venom character. Without Hardy and Venom working so well, “Venom” would have been a complete mess.

“Venom” is the latest Marvel property disconnected from the Marvel Cinematic Universe telling the origin story of Eddie Brock (Tom Hardy) and how he got connected with the dangerous symbiote, Venom. After losing his job and his girlfriend, Eddie is down on his luck trying to make ends meet. After a random encounter with Dr. Dora Skirth (Jenny Slate) where she hires Eddie to break into a top-secret lab, Venom aggressively connects with Eddie along with infecting his body and mind. Having to adapt to the symbiote bonded to him, Eddie is also on the run from the sinister Carlton Drake (Riz Almed) who’s trying to get back his experiment before his illegal secrets are revealed.

The two sole survivors of “Venom” abysmal script is Hardy and Venom. If any film showcases how much of a powerhouse Hardy is in Hollywood right now, it’s “Venom”. Any other actor would have crumbled with the poorly written, misguided script, but Hardy put everything he’s got to offer to carry the film out from the grave. Even in the most idiotic scenes, Hardy manages to make it work. Notice how the character Eddie Brock is not receiving praise, as the anti-hero, tough persona the character was advertised as is missing from the final product. The character acts closer to Doctor Steven Strange rather than Eddie Brock from the comics.

As for the titular character, Venom shares the same praises and complaints as Hardy; great performance with a goofy, misguided written tone. As someone who enjoyed “Spider-Man 3”, I finally understand why fans were angry at the portrayal of Venom. I was unaware that Venom is a separate character from Eddie Brock. Originally believing that Venom was an alternate identity to Brock like Spider-Man was to Peter Parker, I was pleasantly surprised to see in “Venom” that the symbiote was a fleshed out, entertaining character. Even though Venom never reaches a frightening level and plays more like a goofball, the character is pleasantly fun to watch.

Unfortunately, everything besides Hardy and Venom is a complete mess. From the forgettable female love interest from Michelle Williams to the purely evil Carlton Drake villain; the supporting cast is downright terrible. Williams’ character is the most generic, uninteresting lover interest to exist in any mediocre superhero movie. Besides one sole character trait with knowing Venom’s weakness, she is completely useless and demands to be written out of the film. As for the villain, Carlton is as bland and forgettable as you can get. Every moment Carlton is onscreen doesn’t work in the slightest. This villain received no love from the filmmakers who’s sole purpose is to be the forgettable first villain to lead into the more interesting sequel villain.

Two big criticisms “Venom” received before its release is the lack of a connection to Spider-Man and how the film was toned down from an R-rating. As obvious and necessary as it would be to have a Spider-Man backstory for Venom, the alternate origin story for Venom is passable. I am curious why Sony, who still owns a portion of the rights to Spider-Man, didn’t tie the character into their new franchise, but it’s a moot point now. As for the tone down rating, “Venom” really would have benefited from being a film for 17 years old and up. Especially knowing there are 40 minutes cut out of the final film, this final product in theaters doesn’t feel like the desired cut.

“Venom” is a pure example of a terrible film saved by a few great aspects. Hardy and Venom are the only redeeming aspects of the film. Without these two good aspects, this movie would be unwatchable; luckily, its the two main stars of the film. With days between seeing the film and writing this review, it has been difficult whether to declare people to see the film or not. As much as there are some very embarrassing moments, Hardy and Venom really do redeem the terrible parts. Predicting that an extended cut is coming in the near future, I would wait to see “Venom” until it’s available to rent. Maybe people will downright hate it and find the chemistry between Brock and Venom completely idiotic, which is completely understandable. If you’re willing to take a risk in seeing what side you land on, check out “Venom” at your most convenience. 

6/10
